orthamptonshire, England":"Boughton, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Greene","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Green  . In North America, this surname has assimilated cognates from other languages."],"variants":[{"name":"Green","meanings":["English: either a nickname for someone who was fond of dressing in this color (Old English <i>grēne</i>) or was young or immature, or who had played the part of the ‘Green Man’ in the May Day celebrations, or a topographic name for someone who lived near a village green (Middle English <i>grene</i>, a transferred use of the color term). This is one of the most common and widespread of English surnames. In North America it has assimilated cognates from other languages, notably German <b>Grün</b> (see   Gruen  ) and Dutch   Groen  ; compare 7 below. This surname is also very common among African Americans.","English: alternatively, from a Middle English personal name <i>Grene</i>.","Irish: adopted for <b>Ó hUainín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Uainín</i>’, a personal name from a pet form of <i>uaine</i> ‘green’, see   Honan  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Alexander Greene de Boketon was born in 1181, in Boughton, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son with Margaret. He died in 1236, in his hometown, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1181–1236":"1181–1236","1186–Female":"1186–Surnud","1242–Male":"1242–Surnud","1236":"1236","1202":"1202","1242":"1242","1186":"1186","1181":"1181","Boughton, Northamptonshire, England":"Boughton, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1181–1236":"1181–1236","1186–Female":"1186–Kuollut","1242–Male":"1242–Kuollut","1236":"1236","1202":"1202","1242":"1242","1186":"1186","1181":"1181","Boughton, Northamptonshire, England":"Boughton, Northamptonshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1181–1236":"1181–1236","1186–Female":"1186–Décédée","1242–Male":"1242–Décédé","1236":"1236","1202":"1202","1242":"1242","1186":"1186","1181":"1181","Boughton, Northamptonshire, England":"Boughton, Northamptonshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Alexander Greene de Boketon est né en 1181, à Boughton, Northamptonshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Margaret. Il est décédé en 1236, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 55 ans."},"de":{"1181–1236":"1181–1236","1186–Female":"1186–Verstorben","1242–Male":"1242–Verstorben","1236":"1236","1202":"1202","1242":"1242","1186":"1186","1181":"1